The United States expresses concern about the peace process in South Sudan and emphasizes the importance of inclusivity in finding a solution. They condemn the unilateral extension of the government's term in office and urge the government to engage in negotiations that involve all stakeholders. The US calls for the implementation of cessation of hostilities and ceasefire agreements and supports the UN Security Council arms embargo. They are prepared to sanction individuals involved in corruption and those who threaten peace and stability in South Sudan. The US also calls on regional leaders and financial institutions to block and freeze assets related to corrupt activities. They express skepticism towards the leadership of President Kiir and SPLM-IO leader Machar and state that they will not guarantee any agreement or fund the transitional government without a demonstrated commitment to peace, inclusivity, financial accountability, and good governance. The US remains committed to supporting the people of South Sudan and their aspirations for peace and prosperity.